The main objective of the project was to advance our understanding of the mathematical principles underlying efficient and robust statistical estimation techniques tasked with making decisions in the face of uncertainty. The concepts of efficiency and robustness are related to the idea that good, practically relevant methods extract all useful information about the parameter of interestfrom the data and moreover can withstand the presence of errors and noise in the data.


Among the key findings the project are


(a) new algorithms for robust and efficient estimation of averages;


(b) discovery of new properties of the multivariate generalization of the median that have useful applications in statistics;


(c) advances in the theory of algorithms for the high-dimensional linear regression model that underpins many modern data-driven systems;


(d) novel results related to the concepts of interpolation and overparametrization that play an important role in the state-of-the-art mathematical models for modern machine learning methods, as well as results highlighting the interplay between interpolation and robustness;


(e) design of new methods for robust estimation of covariance matrices. Covariance estimation problem serves as a foundation of popular data analysis techniques such as principal component analysis;


(f) new mathematically rigorous Bayesian methods were introduced. Bayesian approach to statistical inference allowsseamless integration of prior beliefs with the evidence contained in the data;


(g) On the purely theoretical side, the project advanced our understanding of U-statistics, a class of objects of utmost importance in statistical sciences.


The project provided training opportunities for students, including several summer research experience sessions for undergraduate students at the University of Southern California. During these sessions, students had an opportunity to explore modern methods of data science and apply them to various data. The project resulted in several Ph.D. dissertation chapters in the areas related to the main goals of the project.


Key outcomes of the project have been disseminated to the research community via publications in the leading journals as well as conference presentations.


